This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) because it deals with modeling neural populations and their responses to external stimuli. Additionally, the paper mentions macaque V1 neurons, which are commonly studied in the field of neuroscience. 

The paper could also belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) because it develops a novel model based on conditional finite mixtures of independent Poisson distributions, which is a machine learning technique. 

Furthermore, the paper mentions that the model can be applied to improve predictions of neural activity based on deep neural networks, which suggests that it could also belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). 

The paper also mentions that it successfully captures stimulus-dependent correlations in the responses of macaque V1 neurons to oriented gratings, which suggests that it could belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CV (Computer Vision). 

Finally, the paper deals with modeling noise correlations in neural populations, which could also make it relevant to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.SD (Sound).
